  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Samuel May, Jr., begins this letter by inviting Miss Weston to attend a meeting of the Massachusetts Anti-Slavery Society, where the &quot;main business relates to an account of Daniel Foster&apos;s, concerning which there is a difference of opinion between himself &amp; me, ...&quot; Samuel May mentions the Estlins&apos; tour of Ireland. Russell Carpenter is to marry Mary Browne of Bridgewater. Samuel May attacks Frederick Douglass. He speaks of Sallie Holley&apos;s nervousness on the lecture platform. He saw S. H. Gay in New York; he was careworn and in low spirits. Samuel May heard Henry Ward Beecher preach.</subfield>
